so here's another version from website tablo about what happened that led up to the assault. that instead of some members of ngt48 who leaked yamaguchi maho‚Äôs address and personal information, it was a *kenkyuusei (trainee) who carelessly told the assaulter the timing yamaguchi maho would return to her dorm.

this story has changed several times through the media.

to quote detective conan: there is always only one truth! (ÂêçÊé¢ÂÅµ„Ç≥„Éä„É≥ : ÁúüÂÆü„ÅØ„ÅÑ„Å§„ÇÇ‰∏Ä„Å§) but so far, the tabloids have been giving us inconsistent versions of their stories.

text: i‚Äôm a #woman, phenomenally. phenomenal woman, that‚Äôs me‚Äîand that‚Äôs you too‚Äîalthough sometimes it can be easy to forget the power that we‚Äôve been given as our birthright. women are #healers, teachers, nurturers, creators, and so much more; yet, we live in a society where women, especially women of color, are often abused, silenced, and ignored. misogyny is alive and well and unfortunately, many women have been the target of egregious displays of #toxicmasculinity for example, 1 in 5 women in the us has been raped and nearly 1 in 3 women has experienced domestic violence in their lifetimes. rape and abuse are so prevalent in our culture that everyone knows someone, or even multiple people, who have been affected by it. perhaps, this person is you. reclaiming your power after a traumatic event can be a difficult task that may require an indefinite amount of time, therapy, and community to help you heal.  wherever you are on your journey, remember that you are not alone. you matter. things do get better.  join me and other women in the #fortwaltonbeach #destinfl community on february 23 from 12-2pm for the first yoni wellness workshop of the year. our focus this time around is on reclaiming our personal power through transformative practices such as #yonimassage, #yonieggs, #yonisteaming, and so much more. come out with us and be the change you‚Äôd like to see in the world! you are welcome here. i love you. #healing #empoweringwomen #divinefeminine #metoo #feminism #female #goddess #local #fortwaltonbeach #revolution #destin #navarrebeach #power

text:
some of the worst crimes against humanity were carried out by people simply 'following orders'. this "i was simply following orders" excuse was made famous during the nuremburg trials in which holocaust organizer adolf eichmann's main defense was that himself and other low level nazi officers were simply following orders.

this allows the blame to be passed along and allows the perpetrator to dissociate and disconnect from their victims and the crime they are committing.

the burden ultimately lies on the order followers and not the order givers.

those that carry out acts, that their conscience tells them is wrong, are 100% responsible.

order followers are submitting themselves to slavery and giving up their autonomy of free will and conscious thought thus perpetuating the system of slavery and repression.

think for yourself.

pick a side.

text:
‚Ä¢ psychoeducation series ‚Ä¢
part 1/1
.
.
#metoo. sounds familiar? 2017 and 2018 were the years when the most trending hashtag on the internet was #metoo. #metoo was actually a movement against sexual harassment and assault that gained mainstream popularity both nationally and internationally. it was this movement that encouraged women to raise their voices against sexual predators and make this; a paramount topic for open discussion. `.
the fact that nearly all cases reported under this thread occured in a professional context is what brings us here to address this issue. `.
harassment is basically any behavior or a combination of physical or verbal behaviors that can be offensive or humiliating to an individual.
`.
it may include objectionable or vulgar remarks, offensive jokes (usually sexual in nature), name calling, inappropriate touching and/or starring, attempting to display pornographic content and deliberately invading one's personal space (coming too close to speak etc)
`.
harassment is not only directed at the person of opposite sex, it may also be directed at the person of same sex. the harasser can be your boss, a supervisor in another department and a co-worker. such a demeaning conduct not only influences the victim mentally but also hinders their work performance and creates a hostile working environment.
`.
in our country where women already have to fight to make their names in a professional sphere, the judgemental foundation of our social fabric makes it even more challenging for them to take a stand for themselves and other women. in such circumstances, adequate knowledge of actions to be taken at a personal front and equally adequate understanding of the national law becomes imperative to break the glass-ceiling!
`.
what does the national law state and how it works? stay connected to know. üôå

ones thing you can do is call your member of congress and ask them to vote ‚Äúyes‚Äù on the h.r. 8 bill - the vote is wed. feb. 6 and  will require that all people have a background check before purchasing a firearm and close the gun show loophole.
let‚Äôs keep guns out of the wrong hands!

i‚Äôve shared this photo and story with my therapist last week, so now i‚Äôm sharing it with you. this was me trying to ‚Äúplay it cool‚Äù while a man less than 10 feet away from me was catcalling/harassing me and my friend during our shoot. judging by the look on my face, i didn‚Äôt play it off well. ‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£
he kept going until we stopped and addressed him. i wished i could‚Äôve cursed him out the way i wanted, but instead i thought ‚Äúwhat if he charges at me while i‚Äôm standing right in front of these steps‚Äù. after telling him we were busy (and cold), he walked away. he then comes back with a friend, telling his friend we were stuck up, and were ganging up on him. thankfully, his friend saw that we were busy and told him to leave us alone. we thanked his friend and walked away. i was so angry. ‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£
i‚Äôm still learning how to find helpful, artistic ways to express my frustrations with sexism, street harassment and sexual harassment. but, the fact that i can‚Äôt be in the street for five minutes without being harassed is not only disheartening, it is inhumane. we have to do better. period. enough. where am i safe? ‚Å£

text:
with the enduring stigma around mental illness and sexual abuse, coming forward to tell our stories takes guts. in order to own our truth, we have to put up with the judgement of a toxic society. 
it also is an act of bravery to stand up for and stand by the people who live their lives to the best of their abilities despite having a mental illness and/or having survived trauma.

at some point, we must all take a stand against injustice, stigma, and bigotry. it is said that the measure of a society is how it treats its most vulnerable.

be strong. join the fight. be a man or woman of integrity. fight for those unable to fight for themselves.

text:
i am a mother, a fiancee, a daughter, a sister, and a friend to the people in my life but in my relationship with myself i am a cheerleader and nurturing friend. ‚ô°

i wasn't always my own best friend. far from it. i had body issues, insecurity issues, numbing out reality issues, a terrible relationship with food, and a lack of belief in my ability to make a difference in this world. ‚ô°

after completing my training in tm meditation my capacity and drive for learning grew exponentially. i then did training in life coaching which helped me outline and get seriously detailed on the life i wanted for myself. 
i bought a condo (my first roots in years) and went back to school to learn about holistic nutrition. ‚ô° 
i still invest in myself daily and have about 5 books on the go at all times. all on different aspects of health and self care. i journal, nourish my body and check in with myself in my daily meditations. my life lessons and open mind have helped me change my inner voice. like the quote says, change your attitude and you will change your world. ‚ô°

i am creating guides and programs that will change the world of my clients. i know i can make difference in how woman experience birth and the postpartum recovery. it is my mission, and i am so glad you are here and willing to learn how you can be part of your personal development. ‚ô°

we can choose to be an active part of our life journey or we can be taken for a ride by a system that does not support the nutritional or mental health of new mammas. womans health is a very new field because just until recently we were seen to be exactly the same as men within the scientific research. ‚ô° 
the #metoo movement is just the beginning of woman standing up and voicing that change needs to happen today. thank you for being part of my journey and i am so excited to inspire you on your adventure through the most profound chapter of your life. 
#birthingnourishedmothers 
#holistichealth #holisticmamma #motheringthemother #mammasdeservebetter #postpartumrevolution #birthingwithoutfear

text: see what people are saying about candy apple butterscotch, #newauthor rebecca macceile‚Äôs debut publication. ‚Äúthis is an impactful read if you have ever experienced any sort of abuse. i appreciate the author‚Äôs candor and willingness to write with such openness. she takes responsibility for herself as much as she describes the lasting effects of trauma.‚Äù ‚Äúit is worth the read. it‚Äôs about a woman empowered and, my god, that is a wonderful thing indeed.‚Äù ‚Äúthe author gets to the point while still painting a very clear and definite picture for the readers and i love that. the accounts of the trauma are laid out in such a way that you know what‚Äôs happening and are able to imagine it but you aren‚Äôt bombarded with intense graphic imagery, which i appreciate as a survivor myself. would definitely recommend!‚Äù ‚Äúthis amazingly written gem takes you inside the author‚Äôs world and keeps you there, making you feel like a discreet ‚Äúbug on the wall.‚Äù i could not put it down.‚Äù ‚Äúi wish everyone would write a memoir. it would be so much easier to understand people. i haven‚Äôt been through anything as violent or traumatic, but i think this story is relatable in a lot of ways. it just makes me see a lot of things differently in every day life. it‚Äôs a big eye opener.‚Äù #onsalenow at the #linkinbio. #kindle and #paperback versions available! also for members of #amazonprime, candy apple butterscotch is available in the #kindlelendinglibrary as well as through #kindleunlimitedbooks! that‚Äôs right you can read for #free. #nonfictionbooks #memoir #metoo #ptsdsurvivor #kindlestoryteller2018  #kindledirectpublishing #onsalenow

jean-baptiste huynh was born in france in 1966, of a french mother and a vietnamese father. as an autodidact, he taught himself photographic lighting and printing techniques, which he mastered to the point of developing a personal style. his pure and timeless photography is recognizable in widely varied themes and subjects: portraits, nudes, minerals and plants, as well as spiritual symbols and emblematic masterpieces.

text_retweet: today im going to talk about how trauma matures you. sadly, it's a balance of living free and young, while parenting ya fucking peers. affects a lot of things, it's a sickness, might not be considered a physical aliement, although still remains. specific groups and communities process and regard these situations more considerately of having to look outside ourselves. groups not being held accountable damages all understanding. did you know there's reasons behind nightmares, night terrors, beyond events that brought them. my life is a night terror. anyhow. there's drugs for these things. weirdly they're beta blockers, blood thinners. during unconscious night terror mares. your blood slows, your body drops temperature, you actually subconciously might feel as though your dying, so you have to wake up, rather than let yourself settle like that. the blood thinners, work to speed up blood flow so you can function normally while at rest. although, thins your blood so much, that if not on a balanced diet, you pass out everywhere, while awake, standing, all the blood in your body leaves your noggin, anywhere. there's been much happening all across the country recently and dealing with eachother, keeping consideration of the events that rerouted our own lives is important. there's also other ways these events affect people. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #dreams #goodandbad p.s. i didn't wake up different, just thought it was a nice repost to address this.

please check out npr's ted talks on this subject!!! soo good. 
i really appreciated ashley judd's talk about how when we think the problem is  just from some rare/few sexual deviants we ignore the reality of the problem.  it's ingrained, cultural, systemic. it's "good men" you see every day. 
and sometimes... the problem is so prevalent, we see it so much we don't recognize sexual assault when we see it because "it's just life" it's what women experience regularly. "it can't be sexual assault".... text: fat. this body made it through 8 months of physical, verbal, emotional, and sexual abuse. this body made it through 4 years of pain and trauma without even realizing it. 2 years of grad school while being slowly paralyzed. 1 year of losing hope, of not living because everyday was a physical nightmare. this body in all its worth and love and scars has made it 6 weeks post op with a surgical implant, metal and a synthetic disc. this body is fat and that is ok, because i am healing. i am letting go and i am learning. #instagram #instagood #instahappy #fatgirl #fatbodiesaregoodbodies #plussize #traumarecovery #spinalcordinjury #orthopedicsurgery #doublechinsarein #curvygirl #honormycurves #honormybody #selfcare #selflove #chicana #chingona #feminista #selenaquintanilla #bodypositive #iweigh #fatpositive #bodyconfidence #allbodiesaregoodbodies #healthymind #loveyourself #inspiration #inspirationalstories #domesticviolencesurvivor #metoo

text: thank you delhi, thank you @nwm_india & the delhi team... no small matter getting together 160 women journalists from more than 20 states speaking so many languages that something or the other was always being translated! but there was one language we all understood, that of being kickass media professionals wherever we were, of pitching stories, chasing sources (& chasing payments as freelancers! ), the highs and lows of reporting, the ethical dilemmas that follow us,  the value of bldg solidarity & the sisterhood! over 3 days discussed news coverage in remote areas of the country, how best to cover the upcoming national elections esp with a gender lens, the pervasiveness of sh ( & we have only uncovered the tip) & need for #metoo interventions esp in the non-eng media, implementing the law with rgd to iccs at media houses,  issues of safety with rgd to journos... plus we honed some skills & had fun together! #sisterhoodofjournalists  #nwmidelhi2019

text:
how many people
will have to add their names
to the #metoo campaign
before people acknowledge this problem?
how many more people like me
will have to go through what i did?
how many more friends do i have to comfort
because another person has gone through this?
how many more before it matters?
- i'm sick of people ignoring these stories // p.w.m.

so i wrote this about a year ago? ish? i still haven't seen much progress and i've met more people who have been assaulted. our stories are still doubted, or even worse, laughed at. when we tell our stories, we told we're lying - making it up for attention. should've said something a long time ago. i was 7 the first time i was assaulted. i didn't even know what rape was, much less tell anyone. flash forward 8 or 9 years and everyone is saying these brave people coming out are lying sluts and yet you expect me to tell a bunch of strangers so they can shred everything apart and blame me? things need to change. we need change.
#metoo

text:
sometimes i'm a bit slow and it took half a century to realize something.

here are two pictures, one from a movie, the other from a series pilot, both in the mid-1960s. you might recognize two of the #actors.

my last interview for a part was around 1970 or so, for a john wayne movie, the cowboys, if i remember correctly. i don't know if i would have been hired or not, but my #mother, who got me into acting around 1962, didn't like the script and was concerned that young actors were getting parts that were unsavory. profanity, yes, and she could see that sex was on the way. pretty baby was still eight years away, and the #metoo revelations decades off, although it was in full swing for the more successful actors. she always talked with me like an adult, explained her concerns and  asked me what i thought. i agreed, not fully #understanding, but #trusting her.

at the time, i'd been slowing down, partly because we'd lost our car, house and apartment. my dad was drinking a lot, divorced, and my mother couldn't work due to depression. she was on disability due to illness stemming from events thirty-plus years past. we didn't have enough to eat and lived in a tiny rental house provided by a kind landlord.

i never realized before that if my mother hadn't pulled me from hollywood, my life might have gone very badly. i was an emotional mess in the next decade and who knows what i might have gone through or what damage i might have done.

the money was very good, and she could have done as other parents and kept me in, pushed me. i loved the work. i'd do acting again in a heartbeat if it didn't mean doing disgusting roles. i did a play some years back, just to see how it went. very fun. "in an imperfect world, #love requires #sacrifice." my mother's life would have been more comfortable if she had #exploited me. i was born in bad circumstances, and she didn't have to allow that, i could have been her second abortion.

but she sacrificed to protect me. many times.

it didn't hit me for fifty years.

thank you, mother, for all you did, the rare lessons you taught me, for respecting me, for always supporting me despite all my failures, ingratitude and sins.

text: #motivationmonday this ones for those who #supportsurvivors out there. step 1) believe them. step 2) just listen step 3) get help if needed. 4) walk with and love them unconditionally. repeat. this sequence may look different depending on the survivors needs/wants throughout their journey at any given moment and at times the survivor may not know what they want/need in any given moment as trauma is often very complex and different for each survivor. sometimes you just being there or a call/text/message/email away is all they need. no advice, just love. meet them where they are at and love. do something fun and love. contribute to self-care routine and love. get basic needs met (food/drink/coffee) and love. validate and love. just listen and love. love above all else. #metoo #survivorsupport #selfcare #justlisten #neveralone #throughitall #healing #love ‚òÇÔ∏èüíúüéÜüåû

„Éª„Éª„Éª
a very nervous, intrigued but excited abby this morning getting ready to head to a refuge and volunteer there. a hair stylist, reflexologist and myself offered our skills on the women today, we managed to do all of the guests and they absolutely loved it, my heart warmed to each and everyone. crazy how a little pamper goes along way and makes such a difference even just a simple brow wax and shape! the reality side of it all was very heart breaking knowing the reason they were staying here could be from fear from their own home, domestic abuse, violence.. the list goes on.
i was shocked to see so many young girlsüò¢
iv never really thought of this type of place because iv been lucky enough to never seek help, but thank god for places like this where women and children can escape too and fend for themselves. a big eye opener and a slap in the face that there are so many places like this around and more than we think are suffering, especially in silence. it‚Äôs all so very secretive as they are in hiding, i think it‚Äôs amazing charities like @elleforelleuk are doing this. i watched lynette today who runs this charity bring in boxes filled with gifts ( moisturisers, shower gels, make up,) just the simple things us woman need, it was like christmas morning! instantly i envied this charity and everyone who volunteers and helps ‚ù§Ô∏è
if you think you have anything like christmas gifts you know you won‚Äôt use or would like to donate something small i‚Äôm going to start collecting them monthly to take with me on my next volunteer days üòä check out @elleforelleuk page! they do amazing events to raise money for the charity too üòçüôãüèΩ #womanhelpingwoman #helpingothers #mentalhealthawareness #womenempowerment #stopabuse

text: "shut up about the victimization! he almost killed you. he raped and murdered and he enjoyed it. he had the same chances as us to choose what he wanted to be. he was no victim. he was a sadistic motherfucker who hated women." the millennium series (the stieg larsson ones) are some of my favorite books. lisbeth salander is one of my favorite female characters. she‚Äôs been portrayed by three actresses. first there is noomi rapace who was the truest incarnation of salander. there‚Äôs rooney mara who actually did a good job also. and then there‚Äôs claire foy who was just not salander at all, which i will get to later. out of the book series and the swedish films ‚Äòthe girl who played with fire‚Äô was my favorite. so you would think that sony would do a sequel to the fincher remake with mara and craig with the second installment. not the fourth book in the series that isn‚Äôt even written by stieg larsson. the two books written by david lagercrantz, who is a horrible writer, were just terrible. he made such a great character terrible and the villains were just bad... in ‚Äòthe girl who takes an eye for an eye‚Äô the villain is simply just an evil doctor woman such a shallow character. there wasn‚Äôt even a story in the last one. it felt lazy and shallow. i‚Äôve recommended the book series to a whole lot of people and i just hope they stop at three because lagercrantz just can‚Äôt develop characters as well as larsson could. so sony was definitely stupid, as usual, not to do the second in the series. you‚Äôd think with this #metoo movement and harvey weinstein sex scandals that they would make a great salander film since she is the woman who seeks vengeance on men who hurt women. (continued in comments‚Ä¶)

text:
the buffalo international jewish film festival is dedicated to providing an educational and entertaining cultural experience to the general community.
now in its 34th year, the festival has striven to bring you the very best new independent international films which should not only amuse and enthrall, but should also invite contemplation on societal issues of ethics and justice.
consider the #metoo dilemma of ‚Äúworking woman‚Äù whose protagonist must support her family, while fending off unwanted advances from her boss.
in ‚Äúthe waldheim waltz‚Äù, witness a case study of how a lying, deceitful power-monger rises to the presidency of his country by concealing his motives and past actions.
‚Äúwho will write our history‚Äù speaks to the authenticity of historical events, as opposed to false interpretations. and ‚Äúthe accountant of auschwitz‚Äù asks us to sit in judgment in a nuanced case of collusion.
additionally, we invite you to attend a presentation by a local film producer with some very impressive credits. this year‚Äôs festival is a feast for both the spirit and the mind.
- mike silverman, chair

if lgbtq peeps get recognized for a holiday why don't straight people? ya know, i'm not completely against them and their stuff, but the fact that a lot of them, if not most of them, need to make it a big deal and say oh my life is so bad because i'm lesbian i must be suffering more than you straight people you'd never understand like congrats? want a sticker? you don't see the majority of us doing that do you? no. it's such a big deal if a member of the lgbt community kills themselves or is harassed but what about the straight people or the one or the other gender people? nothing. you don't hear their stories in the news. it's a bigger deal if a trans person themselves over bullying than a normal person and that isn't okay. i hear it all the time too, with people saying shit like "oh really? you get bullied? what about that lesbian girl over there she gets bullied worse. you're just dramatic" those are actual words that have come out of mouths and it makes me sick that they think so highly of themselves and go so far as to say that normal people can't possibly be any worse off than lgbtq makes me furious. you aren't special you're just different. you don't need some special treatment. you're just another person, just like everybody else, you have your problems and others have theirs. like my god, grow up already and just live your life without telling people their problems are lesser just because they aren't trans or gay or some shit. sorry for the rant bois, if you read this far comment "triggered" or some shit. thanks for reading this far.

text:
i was talking to my sister this week about motherhood, and just how much it can strip you. break you down a little, even. you will never be the same again. 
changed for eternity. 
and that demand that now grips you daily is taxing on your energy levels. especially when your health is not at the top of your list of priorities.

this 'me first' concept is foreign now, right?. it can seem hard to get your head around. i battle with it too. and so i ditched that idea and prefer a , 'me too' approach. because i matter too. i find this so easy and natural to explain to my boys. i matter too. we are all important.

having this mental attitude means i can place my health (all of it, holistically) at the top of my priorities list. and ditch the guilt!

because with my health at the top, i have more energy, a greater happiness, and greater capacity to give to my kids and husband happily. because you know, my cup is fuller.

so girlfriend, where does your health sit on your list & how full is your cup? 
let me know in the comments.

this 'me first' concept is foreign now, right?. it can seem hard to get your head around. i battle with it too. and so i ditched that idea and prefer a , 'me too' approach. because i matter too. i find this so easy and natural to explain to my boys. i matter too. we are all impoant.

having this mental attitude means i can place my health (all of it, holistically) at the top of my priorities list. and ditch the guilt!

because with my health at the top, i have more energy, a greater happiness, and greater capacity to give to my kids and husband happily. because you know, my cup is fuller.

so girlfriend, where does your health sit on your list & how full is your cup? 
let me know in the comments.

text:
day twenty two. read a personal development booküå∏

i don‚Äôt feel great, i feel somewhere between lazy depression and pushing myself out of it. i guess i don‚Äôt make sense.

today walked in woods and talked about rape. 
it took me a year or two to realize and say it out loud. i was raped. somehow i still want to hush it down and say ‚Äújust a little bit, it could have been worse and maybe it doesn‚Äôt count‚Äù, but i should not feel like i deserved it, even if i did make stupid decisions.

met a guy from tinder, i smoked too much weed and got sick. i asked him to take me home, he couldn‚Äôt at that moment, he told me lay down and rest. he tried to kiss me and i said ‚Äúno‚Äù. he raped me and i was to weak to stop it. i don‚Äôt remember how he came, i don‚Äôt remember, how i got home, i don‚Äôt remember how i felt next day.

it shouldn‚Äôt be like that.

i‚Äôm not into development books.
2 years later he sent me friend request on facebook. i haven‚Äôt denied or confirmed for two years.
#selfcare #metoo #winter #forest #weed

text:
dear professor berg, youre single-handedly making the world a far better place. i mean, *male studies* taught by a *white woman* on the heels of the #metoo movement? i love you. and i love you *extra* for not putting "black studies" in place of "whitness studies". i'm over feminist theory, but still. trasgender theory makes up for it. this will be my very first transgender theory class, and i'm very excited. and i love you. i plan to show up nutrient dense and well-rested
.

i can't wait to do a retrospective on the pancake box. i *love* critiquing era-spacific marketing strategies. almost feel like im back at parsons
.

now i will try to make you my advisor, uncomfortably hard
.

and originally, i sought to take this class bc i figured "jennifer" would be like "megan" and "kate spade" her immediate environment, and subsequently id be more able to understand why on earth there is so much disgusting cultural uniformity in health books, as if only medocre white women eat and get sick? well, i certainly can't find the answer here; please accept my apology, professor berg. i love you
.

and i'll store your number in my phone for safe keeping. on direct dial.

üíØ 110% üíØ this is so on point.
.
and it sums up my current discernment practice as i go through this personal and professional rebuild/relaunch. .
i‚Äôm in the very early stages of re-learning how to relate with others from the heart.
.
professionally, this is easy. it‚Äôs my space, it‚Äôs my comfort zone, i am in charge and i have control. .

but out in the world, it‚Äôs a learning process. not every man who locks eyes with me is trying to get something from me... or, are they?
.
my boundaries had been vastly disrespected, now i have to learn to hold them again- but also remain soft, open, loving.
.
developing and appropriately recruiting the various parts of my self when necessary is part of my work with @presenceacademy - gently allowing things to be, to appear, to show me what they actually are/who they actually are, while maintaining faith that ‚Äòthe protector‚Äô part of me is just one instant away.
.
and she‚Äôs a fuccin bad ass.
.
can i keep myself safe?
can i trust other people?
most especially men..?
.
some, yes. some.
getting there. .
.
.
.

text: even though it‚Äôs been over a year since we recorded these next two episodes, and we are now two seasons into the hulu special, we still think our conversations about the book and our local movement are valuable. the media‚Äôs treatment of the judge roy moore & doug jones senate race in alabama did not present the south in a positive light, at least not until our women took a stand against moore‚Äôs sexual misconduct and predation on young girls.  join amaya and i as we interview a panel of women who dressed as handmaids to protest moore‚Äôs candidacy during steve bannon‚Äôs rally. we also discuss atwood‚Äôs ‚Äúthe handmaid‚Äôs tale‚Äù and look at how themes in the book connect to the #metoo movement and other current political issues. we look deep into what the #metoo movement is really about, and we debunk the myth that the movement has gone too far as we discuss the more subtle manifestations of misogyny and exploitation understood by atwood when she wrote her book over 20 years ago.  you can find these episodes and more on at femmsouth.com, soundcloud, itunes, and spotify.  please subscribe and rate our show. #femmsouth #podcast #feministpodcast #southernwomenreading #handmaidstale #handmaidsresistance #women #womenempowerment #womeninmedia #feminization #womempoweringwomen #feministbooks #feministbookstore #southernfeminist #metoomovement #metoo

text:
meet the two recent parsons grads who are challenging china‚Äôs anti-#metoo movement with fashion
#
in 1863, a controversial exhibition titled the ‚Äúsalon des refus√©s‚Äù was held in paris. it featured a selection of paintings by artists like √©douard manet and gustave courbet that had been rejected by the official paris salon, because at the time, they were considered avant-garde and provocative. the works were widely criticized and they outraged the traditional thinkers in french high society, but the public became fascinated by this new style of art and the messaging behind it nonetheless. fast-forward some 150 years later and two recent parsons graduates are carrying on the legacy of the ‚Äúsalon des refus√©s‚Äù in the era of #metoo. yuner shao and ‚Äústef‚Äù puzhen zhou are launching a label called refuse club, named after the influential exhibition and with the intention to raise conversation around a taboo topic.born and raised in chongqing, china, the young designers have created the collection to help highlight the fact that in their home country, the government is still silencing those speaking out in support of the #metoo movement. their debut pieces, which include a deconstructed version of the traditional qipao dress and loosely fitting corsets, are intended to reference the way that acts of sexual violence against women are‚Ä¶

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he‚Äôs the only straight man i‚Äôve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: i finally finished it! it's my #metoo story, i've worked on it since last week. it's not that long, took me like 30 minutes to read but i was still editing it (which i probably i still will later because it's hard for me to just leave it) but it can probably take most people less time than that. i do admit maybe my mom was right that i could've made some different choices but was i the one that was an adult? no. did i actually resist? yes. did i say no? yes. i'm not scared of people asking me questions so if you have any then you can ask. it's the first time i've told anyone the full story so i'm like stressed. before i tell you to click the link in my bio i'd like to let you know there's triggers in it and also it's, well, graphic. the triggers are rape, sexual assault, self harm, choking, physical abuse, and blood. there's also a pedophile but idk if that's anyone's trigger. anyways i don't want to hurt any of you so if those are your triggers than don't read it. it's 6 parts and some parts are worse than others. i think the 4th part is the worst, it was the hardest to write. i mostly wrote this because i started having nightmares more last week and i just felt like i needed all this information to be somewhere other than my mind. but still, read it if you want and don't read it if you have those triggers. thx. ~ camille

text:
for over a decade i walked in secrecy. after i was raped i told one person who didn‚Äôt believe me so i went silent for 5 years, treading water to stay afloat, running when the pain and shame were too much to bear, and turning to every coping mechanism in the book. did you know that suicide attempts for sexual assault survivors are 15 times more likely than for folks who haven‚Äôt experienced that trauma? i was not shocked at all to learn that statistic a couple of years ago. so many of us walk in silence with these wounds that can swallow us whole. it wasn‚Äôt until college when i would tell another soul after she led the way with vulnerability, sharing her abortion experience from high school, letting me know it was safe to share my rape story. we exchanged trauma stories, and she didn‚Äôt know it then, but that changed my world. she opened a wound i‚Äôd buried alive, allowing me to try again to heal it. it didn‚Äôt happen overnight, in fact, it wasn‚Äôt until years later that i would inhale and realize i could really breathe again.

building an emotion processing toolbox and learning to meet my shame with empathy led me to a scar that will always live on my body, but much like the stretch marks on my legs tells a story of how i got here. we don‚Äôt get to control our experiences, or anyone else‚Äôs, and no matter how far down we push them, they will be there, throbbing in pain until we heal them, letting them scab over and turn into a scar that stays with us, but no longer hurts us.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i see you, holding it together, praying that time will heal that wound. sister, i prayed that prayer for a long long time, and perhaps my college pal was the answer as she uncovered it, allowing me to try again to heal it. it won‚Äôt be easy, but it will be worth it. as a gal with a scar now, i can tell ya, that work pays off, maybe for generations.‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

.

‚Ä¢
by the language being spoken by the people attacking her, you could tell this incident took place in benin city, edo state, nigeria. ‚Ä¢

please see my fundraiser on facebook or help me to get some ideas to raise money.  last night i took medications and weed but never knocked out till 5am and woke up 10am late for school.  we didnt hear 2 alarms the way my son and i were tired. so i need help with him so that i can get sleep without depending on anything. nothing helping except rest. i avoid lifting, twisting and used to adapting. i dont work or get child support so i need to raise money for caregiver and home.  inbox me or call me if you are interested in helping me in plantation florida usa.  my nerve damage and spinal cord tethering causes me to overheat, nauseated, spasms, goose bumps, mouth tingling, abdomen spasms and swells, fatigue, pain,  poor appetite, hard to concentrate.  poor sleep. i would love to sleep when i feel like, go out when i feel like but i dont have help with my son 24 hours. i avoid the sun and outdoors sometimes because of the heat or cold.  jamaica too hot and made me get a heat stroke 2018.  but in the usa i also get sick from the heat when it made me dizzy.  my son kaiden renaissance surry who is an empathetic child and understands me well.  we ran away from domestic violence and child abuse to a home where i live with family.  my family comes and goes and are not there when i need emergency help or just  a little massage or drive.  many people coming in and out.  i cannot take the continued abuse from my own family after running away from my ex husband. so i want help to move into own place with a caregiver.  time to heal up from all this trauma.  thank you.

text:
speak your worth 
speak your worth is an empowerment group for any person or persons who's worth has  been questioned or compromised. speak your worth is about overcoming life changing events, depression, abuse, anxiety, etc. 
speak your worth is here to empower, strengthen, support and motivate one another for the present and future. we are given one voice and we are here to speak our own personal worth; so that anyone going through a storm is encouraged to see the light. it is time to break the silence because your voice and life matters. 
#yourvoicematters #speakyourworth #metoo #womenempowerment #moretolife #love #life #befree

text:
maybe you were neglected in physical or emotional ways, but after years of learning how to re-center yourself little by little, you eventually become a queen of mattering ‚Äî you know and ask for what you need regularly, seamlessly, fluently. in bed. out of bed. everywhere. and a confidence starts to drip off your skin. a confidence that says, ‚Äúi‚Äôm worth it.‚Äù .
.
maybe you were exploited with f*ed up power dynamics... but after a long period of learning to cultivate safety and care, you get super into dom/sub stuff ‚Äì rock the power play in the sexiest, safest way.

maybe you were shamed and repressed for your natural erotic nature‚Ä¶ but after years of hiding, dimming or screaming to be heard, you find the heart-based medicine of your sensual expression. and you share it in the places that feel juicy and aligned.

maybe you were manipulated or coerced in subtle or pervasive ways... but after a long time working to differentiate your energy from others‚Äô energy, you become a sovereign energetic jedi sage. in sex. in work. in friendships.

maybe you were physically violated with violence or force... but after years of chronic pain or addiction, you become devoted to vitality and empowered safety. you awaken your power to move things where they need to be. you get super into movement, dance, strength training or jade egg practices.

the truth is, no one gets to live a wound-free life. there‚Äôs no erasing humanity‚Äôs shadows no matter how hard we try.

but within our shadows ‚Äì within the dense, dark depths of our humanness ‚Äì there are potential blueprints of health waiting.

we can walk towards our post-traumatic growth like a calling or a soul quest. we can claim it even though it can be expensive and exhausting. we can put our eyes on the prize of who we might become, what world we might co-create, in the process of transmuting our trauma into gold. .
.
not tryina tie a pretty bow on hardship, but i believe in this possibility. i am living this reality. and i‚Äôm here to help you do so, too.

can you relate? what‚Äôs your post-traumatic growth story look/feel like?

ps ‚Äì¬†i talk more about this in my most recent saved story ‚Äúdevelopmental‚Äù. tune in for hopeful insights.

text:
feminism. the #metoo movement. social media. changing social structures. 
these are just some of the 'things' that have affected modern relationships and what we expect of them. is a good friendship one where we respect each other boundaries and listen with intention? is a good romantic relationship one where each person is allowed to be themselves? is a good familial relationship one where each person is compassionate with the other person's traumas and needs? 
relationships are so complex. they are beautiful and messy and a million things at one. but goddamn do they make life worth it. . . . 
el feminismo. el movimiento #metoo. las redes. los cambios de las estructuras sociales.
estas son solo algunas de las tantas 'cosas' que han afectado las relaciones modernas y lo que esperamos de ellas. ¬øes una buena amistad aquella d√≥nde respetamos los l√≠mites y escuchamos con intenci√≥n? ¬øes una buena relaci√≥n rom√°ntica una en la que a cada persona se le permite ser ellxs mismxs? ¬øes una buena relaci√≥n familiar una en la que cada persona es compasiva con los traumas y necesidades de la otra persona?
las relaciones son tan complejas. son hermosas y desordenadas y un mill√≥n de cosas a la vez. pero caramba, hacen que la vida valga la pena.

text:
hey guys !

rape, sexual harrassment/assualt, physical abuse are the roots of a single tree !

when we hear about any harrassment, we often get to hear women coming out and speaking against them ! 
why not men, transgender people doesn't come out of the closet and speak against to it !

a fear of getting mocked based on gender, sexuality, sexual orientation!

mobbera foundation wants to give a platform for many forgotton stories to voice against these atrocities!

let's hear them, share them and stand against them so that we can create a safe space with gender equality!

i debated for hours whether to post this or not, but after talking with so many women, i decided today i wanted to focus on more than just one woman for the nevaeh project. the silence breakers are a group of women who took the world by storm by creating the #metoo movement. they brought awareness to the reality many face at work and in other environments. as a college student, it seems i know too many women who have had to deal with sexual harassment and so much more. so, to the young girls like nevaeh, you can take the world by storm even when challenges and obstacles come your way. do not be afraid to unite and stand for what you believe in. here is a link to an article about the silence breakers: http://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2017-silence-breakers/ 
#thenevaehproject #empoweringwomen #metoo

text:
it can be exhausting to pretend you‚Äôre on top of everything and feeling fantastic when beneath your ‚Äúbrave face‚Äù there is pain or sadness. some people don‚Äôt want to see your pain because it may remind them of their own and that makes them feel uncomfortable. 
know that you do not need ‚Äúfixing‚Äù but taking time to be with the emotions and share with a trusted friend or loved one who will just listen without attempting to fix you. 
just like everything, these emotions are temporary and they will pass but give yourself time to listen to yourself and acknowledge the emotions. you are not broken, you are human.

text:
two years ago i was at the awkward stage of life, after being heart broken over not being accepted into ndsus design program. this year was supposed to be a year of "finding what to do next". i took up painting, looked at changing my major to fashion and even worked with a russian seamstress and thought of never going back to school. here i was smiling in front of a piece of my work, when in just a few days my life would change forever. i experienced a horrible low that put me in a very dark place. #metoo 
knowing i couldn't live in the same area as the person who hurt me both physically and emotionally, i ventured out to finding another way to pursue my dream of finishing my degree in interior design. to prove to myself and the professors who said i wasn't the right fit for the field. .
.
now two years later i have grown out of that dark place and found a place that brings me joy. i'm excelling in school even more than i ever did at ndsu, i found my passion for design again and i work at a place where i feel loved and appreciated. life has changed so much since february 24th, 2017.
who knows what i'm trying to say, maybe this.........
.
if you are feeling down and think that life isn't going how it should be going. keep working hard and don't give up, trust that everything happens for a reason. find god if that's your thing. be content with being alone. but most importantly keep focused on your goals and dreams. hard work always pays off in the end. .
.
.
.
also take vitamin d to boost your mood in the gloomy winter months!

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
i was silent once, for half my life.
and i found my voice to finally show
that i was here and i was real, to only
find that there were those who cared only for  how i could make them feel. 
i was blind once, for half my life.
and i was finally given the opportunity
to see, and when my eyes eventually
gazed at me, i knew why they started to cry.
i was deaf once, for half my life
and i was finally given aid to hear, and the
first sound to grace my ears was music from 
the muscle in my chest.
music that was here to stay.
i was a victim once, for half my life. 
prey to those that hunt, until i finally heard
the truth i needed to find my own words.
i was 15 then 20 then 25 and now.
now i'm a woman who can tell you how.
how to breathe under water and dance in the
sky, and i can tell you the when and the why, but instead i'd rather tell you that my voice is one of millions, one of yours and his and hers.
one of too many too late too broken and too
afraid too lost too alone. i would rather you hear my strength than see my face and i pray that you know the power of my will, and 
the conviction of my words.
i was a victim, once. 
for half my life.
and now.
...

text:
"maria with barbara" motion.

postures, gestures, movements and figures... time of study. 
working on a new piece but i really hope to show you some photos of my last site specific artwork that evolve from this series of photographs from the performance. 
at this stage of the body of work the lights take importance and we created a purplish atmosphere through them.

in this ongoing body of work the main concepts are: body distortions, body extensions and personal space. explored through photography, performance and site specific installation with a series of sellotape sculptural garments.  collaboration work with @intoxication_relation as a living sculpture. .

text:
i used to hate the scars on my back, but now i wear them with grace.

i used to lie about how i got them, now i can tell you straight face to face.

unlike most people in day to day life, most of my scars don‚Äôt have funny stories behind them. they have memories attached to abuse along with memories attached to old pain. over the years, i‚Äôve watched them fade into faint lines or blotches. if i ever let the sun kiss my skin long enough, my scars become more prominent. i used to hide behind clothes to not share that side of my childhood to the world. but, as i‚Äôve grown into the woman i am now, i look at my scars and smile... because in a twisted way: they make me happy. they show how much of a formidable force i am to be reckoned with- how strong i can be. 
you may just only see the result of a girl trying to not laugh as her friend (@dennisecardenas ü•∞) climbs onto a chair and stands on it in the middle of dave and buster‚Äôs to take a picture of her perched on a stool. but, i see a woman who‚Äôs finally found her peace with a skin she used to hate. 
love the skin you‚Äôre in no matter what story it tells. i promise it‚Äôs beautiful no matter what that story is. üíô

text:
"the weird one"

hanging out with anirudh, catching snakes, playing football with the guys in school, almost drowning in a lake while catching fish. this pretty much summed up my eventful childhood. i've always been someone who doesn't let things affect me that much. i move on and take things as they come.
since i was little, somehow through biology classes 'down syndrome' was the thing that stood out to me. i still remember the first day i entered a school next to my house. there was velu walking towards me with a vijay movie song played by one of his friends. he apparently had been seeing me for really long and had love failure when it didnt work out. it was hilarious and amazing at the same time. most people who look at my stories ask me for details about the school but no one ever follows up. they don't show it in their actions, it‚Äôs quite frustrating. it‚Äôd be nice if people lived up to their words.
there was this once when i shaved my head in aid of cancer patients and started this videos/rants in a funny way on youtube about how pathetic our society is and people in general, out of no where it got so much recognition and people started texting me asking me when the next one was out. #metoo happened to me about 4 years ago when over 200 women had sent me messages about their personal experiences after watching my video. i was so shocked and it kinda upset me. i questioned myself if all we want to do is just laugh at rants and do nothing about issues. that's one of the reasons i usually work best by myself. even in my makeup life, it's mostly me doing everything by myself. 
the first time i did makeup for someone, it was a request from a friend and i realised that i liked it, so did a few gigs for free and decided to see if someone will actually pay me for it, and voila i managed to do over 80 happy brides in 2018. when the tough gets going, i just cut off from everything and go grab my surf board and hit the waves, one sport where i feel we dont pollute nature and rather play with it. :)
say hi to the multi-talented @anushaswamy! 
do reach out to her for any wedding make-up or if you guys are interested in working with her school. 
#peopleofmezze

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
he threatened me, violated himself on me, he sexual abused me for long time. i cried for help to my big sister as she was visiting me back then, but that was before i knew she had a crush on that cop who was actually married to an arabic woman and abusing me. he was a cop and was sent to work with me as a mentor in order to make me stop going to war. and the other was my own blood, my own brother, but that happened when i was only a child. this is why my christian uncle took care of me before taking his own life. both, brother and cop, should have protected me, but both used their violations and clean cv to violate themselves on me and make me look like the liar and sick minded. i cried in my court trial the first time i saw the judge was letting the cop and my brothers words against me. my other brother said i was a #pjak member (pkk in iran) and the cop was saying i was a #pkk and sick. the same did the cop in all my court trials. i told the judge the truth but she said ‚Äúi‚Äôm sorry but it‚Äôs written you are sick‚Äù 
i want to ask for forgiveness from the girls who finally reported that cop. a group of cops came to my cell while i was the only woman in the largest prison in dk with relatives to dead danish isis fighters right underneath my cell. they had investigated the case and found a lot.. i‚Äôm more than sorry that i couldn‚Äôt report the cop. when i was young and reported my brother it only backfired on me. so why would anyone believe a ‚Äúsick-terrorist‚Äù? you are all stronger than me dear girls, and i truly ask for your forgiveness. 
2 months after my final court trial the cop was in court and he lost.  he was sentence to 1y in jail. they had prepared 10 court days against him but he admitted everything on the first day. for my brother who also did that, well it is too many years ago and therefore a dead case. 
may god forgive us all.

#book #freedomfighter #joannapalani #denmark #kurdish #kurdistan #2014 #authorities #metoo #abused #survived #cops

text_retweet:
#repost from @backto_muslimidentity with @regram.app ... perempuan butuh syariat islam, bukan ruu pks
.
pengamat politik dan pemerhati perempuan, pratama julia sunjandari, menilai alasan tingginya angka kekerasan seksual di indonesia yang menjadi latar belakang legalisasi rancangan undang undang (ruu) penghapusan kekerasan seksual (pks) sungguh mengada-ada.

pasalnya, menurut pratma, bukan sekadar ada umbrella act lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya. atau gerakan #metoo yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.

pratma lalu mengungkap tiga alasan kalangan feminis ngotot ingin melegalisasi ruu pks, ‚Äúpertama menyuburkan perilaku sekuler liberal. muatan srhr (sexual and reproductive healths rights) sebagai ‚Äòamanah‚Äô beijing platform for action (bpfa) amat kuat. frasa ‚Äòkontrol seksual‚Äô itu menegaskan daulat atas tubuh sehingga seorang istri berhak menolak hamil atau menolak ajakan suaminya ke tempat tidur. termasuk hak untuk meluapkan orientasi seksual pada apapun atau siapapun.‚Äù kedua, kata pratma julia, merusak keluarga terutama relasi suami istri. tak ada lagi qawwam (pemimpin) dalam rumah tangga termasuk dalam hubungan yang amat privat. ketiga, menikam syariat islam. kalangan liberal, dengan dukungan negara leluasa mengadvokasi umat untuk tidak lagi patuh pada hukum allah. ‚Äúmenjadi keharusan bagi kaum muslimin untuk menolak dan mencegah kemunkaran ini dengan aksi nyata,‚Äù ungkapnya kepada mnews, rabu (30/1/2019). pratma kemudian menjelaskan bahwa umat islam harus berupaya menegakkan syariat islam kaffah sebagai solusi persoalan kekerasan terhadap perempuan, ‚Äútidak kalah penting mengedukasi umat bahwa persoalan kekerasan seksual, bahkan pelecehan kehormatan perempuan tak akan terjadi jika khilafah tegak. syariat kaffah itu memiliki hukum yang amat memuliakan manusia apalagi perempuan dengan hukum-hukum sistem pergaulannya,‚Äù tuka

text:
episode 3 is live! meet linda taliaferro! 
i had the absolute privilege of interviewing linda on my first podcast interview. 
linda and i met at yoga and i knew from moment one that she is a badass. she has a great vibe, a contagious smile and a gentle confidence that fills the room. 
linda also has an incredible and powerful story! she is a powerhouse in the corporate world and an inspirational leader in her side hustle, helping other woman procure their seat at the table. 
i think we can all relate to her story of hardship and redemption. she is vulnerable and open. she is a bright light and i am grateful to know her. 
podcast link in bio https://www.stitcher.com/s?eid=58583674&autoplay=1

live on stitcher and buzzsprout, spotify should show up asap. 
follow her here: 
http://www.instagram.com/ltsthetee
http://www.facebook.com/extraeffort
http://www.linkedin.com/in/lindataliaferro
https://www.theteellc.com/

‚†Ä
vincent dance theatre‚Äôs film installation explores the effect of sexual pressure on young women and girls. following the screening of a scene from the film, charlotte vincent, artistic director of vincent dance theatre, talks about the research and creative process of making virgin territory and how the company has used this and other pieces to introduce important issues to new audiences. she is joined by representatives of oasis, the medaille trust, not buying it and other organisations concerned with women‚Äôs safety, in an exploration of how we can prevent and eradicate sexual violence.‚†Ä

text:
**trigger warning: mental health, sexual assault, suicide** #yarnlovechallenge day 5 prompt: substitutions.

like many crafters, i have a history of mental health issues.  i've suffered from depression for most of my life, starting in my teens after i was raped.  i have no problem talking candidly about this, particularly since the creation of the #metoo movement.

experiencing this trauma made me a very angry adolescent and i also had issues with recreational drugs and self harm- i became very self destructive.  i've done a lot of self-analysis over the years and i know that my assault is the root cause of my control issues. 
since being diagnosed with post-natal depression and then psychosis, i've been on a high dose of sertraline and also buspirone. these help with depression and anxiety.  at my worst i was also consumed by suicidal thoughts, and i do mean consumed. 
why am i telling you this? because crafting has become my substitute. i'm a person that needs to be busy and active *all* the time or my mood starts to slip. i *need* to create. i *need* to be working with my hands.

i'm now down to 50mg sertraline every other day and hope to be completely weaned off in a few weeks.  buspirone i dont take often, just when i feel the need (maybe once a month). i know a lot of you use fibre crafts in the same way. whether it's to calm a busy mind, keep your hands busy or just give you something to focus on.

#itsoknottobeok #semicolonproject #mentalhealthadvocate #mentalhealthawareness #creativemind #yarnlovechallenge2019

text_retweet:
signal boost. jenn welch is great.

#repost @jennwelchnow:
„Éª„Éª„Éª
from 2016 to 2018, i taught improv to beginners while also attending weekly sessions with a trauma therapist following a sexual assault. during that time, i found a number of surprising connections between the skills i taught in the classroom and the skills i learned in the therapists office. but most importantly, i noticed that even when i walked into the classroom feeling powerless, panicked or triggered, i consistently walked out of my three-hour classes feeling powerful, joyful and free. .
.
i want to help other survivors feel that same relief. .
.
power through play: improv for survivors is a two-day workshop designed to introduce the core concepts of improv (‚Äúyes, and,‚Äù listen and react, discovery not invention) using performance games and exercises in a trauma-informed classroom. throughout the workshop students are encouraged to discuss, establish and respect boundaries, so they can get out of their comfort zone while avoiding the danger zone.
.
this is not therapy - there's no requirement to discuss your trauma, we will not be doing any trauma-related role-play. if there's any crying, it will be from laughter.
.
the intention of this workshop is to give survivors a respite from their trauma. it‚Äôs a space to rediscover our power through play.
.
this first session is open to female and non-binary students. eventually i hope to hold workshops for anyone who's dealing with trauma. .
.
for more details and to sign up, check out the link in my bio.
.
#improv #classes #nyc #metoo #selfcare @safehorizon @cvtcnyc @nycalliance

text:
‚Äôi was a victim too‚Äô ‚Äì uche jombo speaks on sexual assault in nollywood
.
.
the 39-year-old actress, screen writer & producer, made this disclosure in an interview with hiptv while speaking on the widespread allegations of sexual assault on upcoming actresses. ‚Äúi‚Äôve been in that kind of situation twice during my starting days,‚Äù she said. ‚Äúi rehearsed for almost two weeks only to come next and find that someone else was reading my role because i declined the request to ‚Äòsee me‚Äô (for sex). ‚Äúi wept seriously, i was hurt but four to five years later, i made it big.‚Äù explaining how she survived and maintained her stance at the time, jombo said: ‚Äúit is personal integrity. in my days, we move on when we‚Äôre denied opportunities for refusing to give in to sexual demands. ‚Äúsometimes, it‚Äôs your individual strength, drive and process that matters. what takes some six months to accomplish might take others six years. ‚Äúare you ready to wait for your time or you just want a shortcut that leads to no long-lasting opportunity? if you want the shortcut, chances are that there are people willing to give it.‚Äù jombo said people who engage in such acts should be called out explaining that this would force nollywood recruiters and opportunity givers who indulge in such acts to ‚Äúbe humans again‚Äù. #ijeomadaisy #uchejombo #nollywood #metoo

.
feminisme selayaknya keberadaan perempuan hadir melintasi batas-batas negara. menggugat sistem patriarki dalam setiap aspek kehidupan bermasyarakat. .

text:
in reading an article this weekend about a new yoga class called feelosophy, i am struck with the hope that the theme of our book is not an isolated intention. wendy martin and i launched this at the height of #metoo, on the claim that right touch can change our world. now more than ever, we need to connect, we need to land and we need to unite.

the necessity of touch is a resource for teachers and yogis alike who want to break down postures to their bare bones for greater clarity through detailed instructions on how to assist. it is beautiful with all pics done by my partner paul. 
our hope is that it will help you to pause, inhale and exhale, sink into your body and learn to love again.
paper version www.ahimsa.ca
e-book version www.allieandwendy.thinkific.com

____________________________

text:
happy catholic schools week! the week is technically over, but we have so many amazing alumnae that we need to highlight a few more. today, we are pleased to present bridget todd '03. @bridgetmarieindc 
bridget got her start teaching courses on writing and social change at howard university. since then, she‚Äôs trained human rights activists in australia, led strategy for organizations like the women‚Äôs march, and msnbc, and ran programmatic content for the new organizing institute. she‚Äôs questioned obama about policy on mtv and been on ‚Äúthe daily show.‚Äù bridget explores feminist activism with the 2.5 million listeners of her popular podcast stuff mom never told you. @stuffmomnevertoldyou she also teams up with afropunk, a music and culture festival, to produce a global salon where she‚Äôs hosted folks like ava duvernay and #metoo creator tarana burke. 
bridget‚Äôs work has been covered in teen vogue and she was named a notable woman in politics by paper magazine.

text:
#savethedate 3-23-19 
join #nyccelebrateswomen #brunch- #fundraiser and let‚Äôs continue the conversation about #metoo in the latina community. proceeds from this event will benefit @nmicnyc. please click the link on the bio to learn more about this organization serving #nyc #bronx #manhattan 
this mural by puerto rican artist @yasminhernandezart honors the common histories and struggles of mexicans and puerto ricans and is a call for continued and increased solidarity between the two communities. visually, the concept is inspired by #fridakahlo ‚Äòs painting, ‚Äúlas dos fridas.‚Äù in my design for ‚Äúsoldaderas‚Äù however, frida kahlo sits holding the hand of the equally fierce puerto rican poet, #juliadeburgos. the image was partly informed by my work as an artist educator at el museo del barrio in new york city (2002-2009). while there, i worked with various kahlo pieces as well as casasola's photo archive documenting the mexican revolution, including images of soldaderas-women soldiers of the revolution. though i had the idea for this mural since around 2005, it was not until the spring of 2011, through a collaboration between art for change, hope community, inc and el barrio arts cluster that the project was finally able to get off the ground. i began working on ‚Äúsoldaderas‚Äù on friday, june 3rd, 2011 at the modesto flores community garden on lexington avenue between 104th and 105th streets and unveiled it on july 6 of that year. #visitelbarrio

text:
i've learnt from home,
that indifference is love,
so every time a person looks away from me,
my heart grows fonder,
i wonder what it would be like
waking up to him
whispering sweet nothings,
being on the receiving end of love

because i've learnt from home,
love is indifference.
